insert into Reviews
	values('ur0342623','Victor Sjostrom stars in Ingmar Bergmans Wild Strawberries, from 1957.As most everyone knows, Victor Sjostrom was the Swedish and Hollywood director Victor Seastrom who ultimately quit directing and acted full-time in theater and film. I dont think multitalented covers it. His acting, as his directing, is magnificent.Here he is Professor Isak Borg, a man about to get a prestigious award. As he contemplates his life, however, he has strange dreams. As he talks to his daughter-in-law (Ingrid Thulin), he realizes that the only difference between his life and death is the coffin. In choosing a lonely, cutoff existence and a life of cold detachment, Borg realizes that he is already dead.This sounds like depressing Bergman, but in fact, Isak learns something as he travels to get his award. Along the way, he and his daughter-in-law Marianne agree to give a ride to some young people, two boys and a girl named Sara, which is the name of Isaks first love, his cousin. Like the woman he loved, Sara is being sought after by both boys, and she flirts with each one. In Isaks life, his Sara fell for his brother. The situation brings back Isaks childhood to him, and he relives family experiences when he visits his old home and later, his 96-year-old mother and sees her own coldness.Isak and Marianne also give a ride to a married couple whose car has broken down. But their fighting is reminiscent of Isaks own marriage (and Mariannes to Isaks son, too, for that matter), and Marianne asks them to get out of the car."Wild Strawberries," referring to the strawberries that grew on the land of Isaks family home, is the story of a man coming to grips with his life - a life full of accomplishment but not many human connections.The most striking thing about this black and white film is the cinematography - the starkness of Isaks dreams, the family all in white against the Swedish landscape - so many stunning images.People call this film optimistic and uplifting, and it is. It is also profound, emotional, and very warm. Sjostrom shows us a charming old man whose niceness is on the surface only. While Marianne says that she doesnt like him very much, the young people love him and buy into his facade because they sense the real man he is afraid to show others.Bergman tells us that lifes questions arent answered right away - sometimes, it takes a lifetime.',10,'30 June 2011','0050986');
