insert into Reviews
	values('ur13134536','Big Lebowski, The (1998) *** (out of 4) "The Dude" Lebowski (Jeff Bridges) gets mistaken for a millionaire Lebowski and soon hes pulled into a big mystery when that rich guys skank girlfriend is kidnapped by some unknown men. Soon The Dude must try and figure out whos pulling all the strings but of course in between his bowling league and dope. The "plot" of THE BIG LEBOWSKI is probably the least important thing because as a mystery it really doesnt work for a couple reasons. One is that its too easy to figure out what really happened and the second is that you really dont care too much. The movie works because of the terrific characters and I dont think its an overstatement to say that theyre some of the most memorable of any film of the decade. The screenplay by the Coen brothers works so well because the characters are so well developed and theyve gotten some incredibly talented actors to bring them to life. Even the smallest parts in the film feature a fair number of known actors including a few who would go onto win Oscars. The entire film goes around Bridges who is pitch-perfect as The Dude. This laid back type of character is one Bridges had been playing for decades by this point but add in the dope, the strange dialogue and the supporting characters and you can say youve never seen a lazy bum like this one. Bridges is just so believable in the part that you not once feel as if youre seeing a performance but instead youre seeing a real loser caught up in the situation. John Goodman plays his Vietnam buddy and its a real shame that he gets so overlooked because he delivers perhaps the funniest performance in the film. Countless movies have done the "crazed Vietnam" bit to death but Goodman comes across so original that you cant help but feel that hes one of the best who has ever done it. I just love the way hes able to go from calm to psycho and back to calm in the matter of seconds. The supporting cast is just as impressive with Julianne Moore, Steve Buscemi, David Huddleston, Tara Reid, Philip Seymour Hoffman and John Turturro are all terrific in their bit parts as well. The chemistry that the supporting players have with Bridges is another strong selling point. Another major plus is the soundtrack, which features the likes of Bob Dylan, Creedence Clearwater Revival, Elvis Costello, Santana, the Eagles and many more. I think the one downside to the film is that since the mystery doesnt work, the extended 117-minute running time feels a bit too long and you cant help but feel that the story could have been wrapped up in less time. With that said, there are countless big laughs to be had here and its certainly true that you never know where the comedy is going to come from and that helps keep the thing moving. The performances, especially Bridges and Goodman, makes this film a true cult classic.',0,'24 June 2011','0118715');
