	values('0113247','La haine','',8.1,'15','','');
insert into Directs
	values('Mathieu Kassovitz','0113247');
insert into Writes
	values('Mathieu Kassovitz','0113247');
insert into Reviews
	values('ur0855231','Why do people riot? Why do things become so pent up, that the only solution to the ill-feeling is a violent eruption of chaos and violence? In post-war Britain, probably the worst of what immediately preceded the events that unfold in "La Haine" occurred in 1981 and 2011, when communities and often entire cities burnt for several days with conflicting explanations as to why. Conclusions are often reached along racial; economic and moral grounds - might all play their own part?Commenting on 1981, John Tyndall lamented as to how it was inevitable that trouble would erupt when non-white citizens, often of a completely different temperament; character and cultural stock, were thrust into compact post-war urban areas not built for this purpose. The Prime Minister of the time, Margaret Thatcher, blamed in her memoir unemployment and the erosion of moral fibre brought about by 60s reform: personal pride and a sense of community had disappeared. Explaining away the nightmare of 2011, Laurie Penny deduced an austerity drive on the things that made life bearable (youth centres and jobseekers allowances) as being the catalyst for the trouble - that, and the incessant police harassment.France is not a place I can speak for with any tremendous authority - I imagine the deductions are largely the same. When, years ago, I first saw "La Haine", a 1995 guerrilla film starring amateurs and made by first timers, I found it kinetic and oddly enjoyable in the way an action film might be. Seeing it a second time, I was struck by how little I appreciated it first time as a piece told from a characters (Hubert) point of view as he worried for the future of one of his friends, who seemed to be heading the way of violence and criminality. Watching it years later; being able to appreciate its social commentaries, and the particularly fine lines the film treads between taking sides within these commentaries, has embedded it as one of my all-time favourite films."La Haine" unfolds in the wake of a night of severe rioting in a Parisian suburb, with characters SaÃ¯d (SaÃ¯d Taghmaoui); Vincent (Vincent Cassel) and the aforementioned Hubert (Hubert KoundÃ©) being those whom the film follows. The three are Arabic; Jewish and black - deliberately epitomising the diversity of the banlieues. There is evident tension between the cops and the local kids, pre-eminently down to the fact a local boy named Abdul - a friend of the threesome - has been beaten so badly he is in hospital.Meanwhile, somebody somewhere on the estate has a policemans gun which was lost amidst the chaos - things could blow up at any moment. Capturing the sense of a group fighting against the odds, Mathieu Kassovitz begins the piece with a character quoting from "The Magnificent Seven", while another character separately re-enacts scenes from "Taxi Driver", which of course ended in a bloody rampage when the lead becomes besotted with firearms.The film portrays a society tearing itself apart, confirming said notion through the use of Huberts narration, although how accurate the warning shot has proven to be can only be answered by somebody living on the frontline of where it depicts. Perhaps unsubtly, Kassovitz interjects coverage of the crisis in Bosnia unfolding at the same time on a large television screen as the boys wait around at a shopping mall - it is no coincidence, with "La Haine" already all too keen to remind us that Paris is a melting pot of skinheads; middle class Le Pen voters; kids from the ghetto and metropolitan champagne-socialist types who, even when the problem lands flush at their feet, are clueless as to how to respond to it.But the film is far from a mere hatchet job - there is no feeling sorry for ones self, or providing the audience with soppy lectures on how its all everybody elses fault. In the wake of the rioting; burning and generalised madness, it is the working man and the very people who live in the banlieues who suffer most: fire has gutted the gym Hubert owned, while another friend had his car torched overnight and so cannot go to work in order to live. There is a palpable sense that the rioting has only incensed the police further and very little political ground has been gained. Just who is the winner here?Writing for Sight and Sound in 1995, Keith Reader quotes Kassovitz that "La Haine" is meant to be understood as an anti-police film, but the police are rarely portrayed as anything else other than people merely trying to do their job: the clearing of a rooftop picnic; guarding Abduls hospital room, etc. Later on in central Paris, SaÃ¯d is stunned at how one policeman even refers to him as sir when getting directions and a plain clothes officer back on the estate is more than helpful in his relationship with the boys. Nobody, however, could condone the behaviour of our leads when they gate-crash a gallery, nor indeed wish that anybody might escape the police pursuit which erupts in the wake of somebody taking aim at a cop car with a shotgun.The film still holds that kinetic feel to it years later. That is despite the fact it is far from some kind of deliberately made entertainment - shootings and getaways occur, but they are not designed to put smiles on our faces. Like war films, we grimace at the sound of a gun, which may or may not be the point Kassovitz is trying to make: like Bosnia, Paris is a warzone, albeit only comparatively. When, however, the three lads are stuck in the centre of the city; Vincent begins to feel compelled to shoot a policeman and desperation sets in, the film cannot help but excrete a kind of rabid energy maybe akin to the final acts of a blockbuster. Unquestionably, the film is one of raw power and energy; at once terrifying and alarming - one which is startling every time it is viewed.',10,'26 June 2008','0113247');
